This homework is more or less a tutorial that helps you set up the command line tools used in this course, and familiarizes you with the format of the submission requirement. As a pre-requisite of this homework, Install R and then RStudio (the free version of Rstudio Desktop). This homework is due on Jan 22 before class.

You can download a copy of this Rmd file on the course website and use as template for your homework.

  1. Create a folder named ds202_hw1, and create an RMarkDown file hw1.Rmd under this folder to include your solutions. The file and folder names are case-sensitive, which means hw1.Rmd and HW1.rmd are different. It is crucial to follow the exact folder structure and file names, so that your homework can be reproduced and graded by an automated script.

  2. Write your name and Github username in the YAML of your homework Rmd file.

  3. Write a paragraph (<100 words) describing a job that you think is related to data science. Write your paragraph in R Markdown in a nice format to read. Include at least

    1. a link
    2. an image
    3. an italized and a bolded word.

A Business Intelligence Developer is a person who oversees systems for companies to allow them to solve problems analytically. They are excellent communicators and this allows them to talk to other workers to find the problem and create solutions. This link follows are article about this job.

This is a picture of stocks. A BID may have to analyze these graphs and certian data to allow them to find the best stocks to invest.

  1. To make sure your R and Rstudio installation is correct, find the version of R by entering version into the R console. Put this command into a R code trunk in your Rmd file to automatically include the R version in your report.
version

## nickname       Action of the Toes

  1. Install git.

    • If you are on Windows operating system:
      1. Install Git for Windows. In particular, we will need to use the Git Bash (not the Git GUI).
      2. After installation, set up Rstudio to use Git bash as the shell for the Terminal: Open RStudio, click Tools–Global Options–Terminal; under Shells, select Git Bash; click OK.
      3. In the main menu of RStudio: click Tools–Terminal–New Terminal. If you have a $ before your prompt, then you should not need to do anything.
    • If you are on Linux or macOS, Git has probably been correctly configured by default, so nothing needs to be installed. Just click the Terminal tab (above the R Console).

  2. What is the version of your Git? To find out, go to the Terminal tab in RStudio (right to the Console tab), and type in the following command. If it works, this shows that the setup of your terminal and Git is correct. Then explore the bash command line and Git.

    git --version
git --version
## git version 2.21.0 (Apple Git-122.2)

  1. Configure Git by modifying and entering the following commands into the terminal

    git config user.name "your first and last name"
git config user.email "yourEmail"

  2. Register a GitHub account. What is your username?
